Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/parliamentActInvokedTo
Object: Relates an invocation of the Parliament Act to a Public Bill in the new session.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/MemberLeadership
Object: The leadership of a Public Bill by a Member. It is possible for the leadership of a Public Bill to pass to a different Member, for example: if a Member is elevated to the House of Lords.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/sponsorshipByGovernmentOrganisation
Object: Relates a departmental sponsorship to the Government organisation sponsoring a Public Bill at a point in time.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/DraftBill
Object: A draft form of a Government bill issued before being introduced as a Public Bill to Parliament. A draft bill is available to be examined either by a Commons or Lords select committee, or by a joint committee of both Houses of Parliament created for that purpose. This process of examining the draft bill is known as 'pre-legislative scrutiny'

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/Session
Object: A period during which Parliament is able to conduct business on days of its choosing. A session is within a Parliament period. The first session of a Parliament begins on the same day as the Parliament period and ends on a day named in a subsequent prorogation proclamation. Subsequent sessions within the Parliament period begin and end on dates named in subsequent prorogation proclamations. The final session of a Parliament ends either with prorogation followed by dissolution or with dissolution. Session periods are the same for both Houses.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/isIn
Object: Relates a bill to the session in which it was presented. A bill will always be in one session.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/carriedOverTo
Object: Relates the act of being carried over to the bill in the new session.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/PublicBill
Object: A proposal for a new Act of Parliament with general application across the whole population, without that application being limited to particular groups, people or places. A Public Bill is either a Government Bill or a Private Members' Bill.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/ActOfParliament
Object: An Act of Parliament creates, amends or repeals legislation. An Act is a Bill having been passed by Parliament and been given Royal Assent. Acts of Parliament which are in force comprise statute law.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/carriedOverFrom
Object: Relates the act of being carried over to the bill in the preceding session.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/precededBy
Object: Relates a Public Bill to the Draft Bill which preceded it. A Public Bill may be preceded by one Draft Bill, or none. A Draft Bill may be followed by one Public Bill, or none.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/DepartmentalSponsorship
Object: The sponsorship of a Public Bill by a Government organisation. If the machinery of Government changes during the passage of a bill, it is possible for the sponsorship of that bill to pass to a different Government organisation.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/HybridBill
Object: A hybrid bill is a public bill having general application across the whole population, whilst also having been examined and found to differently affect the interests of particular groups, people or places. Hybrid bills are presented as public bills. If examined and found to be hybrid, they follow a procedure including parts of the private bill procedure.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/hasMemberLeadership
Object: Relates a Public Bill to a leadership by a Member at a point in time. A Public Bill may have one or more leading Members, or none in the case of a Private Members' Bill.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/leadershipByIncumbency
Object: Relates a Member leadership to the incumbency of a Member in a Government position leading a Public Bill at a point in time.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/Bill
Object: A proposal for a new Act of Parliament.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/sponsorshipByIncumbency
Object: Relates a Member sponsorship to the House seat incumbency of a Member sponsoring a Public Bill at a point in time.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/ParliamentActProcedureInvocation
Object: The Parliament Acts of 1911 and 1949 limit the power of the House of Lords in relation to the House of Commons. The Acts removed the rights of the Lords to pass bills on public tax and spending, to veto or to indefinitely delay the progress of Public Bills. Where a bill is passed by the House of Commons and rejected by the House of Lords in the same session, the Government may introduce a similar bill in the following session. If the House of Commons invokes the Parliament Act, the House of Lords has one month to agree to the bill, otherwise the Commons may pass the bill unilaterally. The similarity of a bill being introduced in a following session is not made explicit until the Speaker certifies the bill as being subject to the Parliament Act.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/parliamentActInvokedFrom
Object: Relates an invocation of the Parliament Act to a Public Bill in the preceding session.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/MemberSponsorship
Object: The sponsorship of a Public Bill by a Member. It is possible for the sponsorship of a Public Bill to pass to a different Member, for example: if a Member is elevated to the House of Lords.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/explains
Object: Relates an explanatory note to the bill whose purpose it explains.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/GovernmentOrganisation
Object: Government departments, agencies and public bodies which have responsibility for a specific sector of public administration.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/hasDepartmentalSponsorship
Object: Relates a Public Bill to a sponsorship by a Government department at a point in time. A Public Bill may have one or more departmental sponsorships over time, or none in the case of a Private Members' Bill.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/hasMemberSponsorship
Object: Relates a Public Bill to a sponsorship by a Member at a point in time. A Public Bill may have one or more Member sponsorships over time, or none in the case of a Government Bill.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/Incumbency
Object: The holding of a position by a person, including the time period for which this was the case. For example, Philip Hammond holding the position of Foreign Secretary between two dates.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/CarryOver
Object: The act of carrying a bill over from a session to the following session. A bill being carried over results in the creation of a new bill in the new session, the text of the new bill being the text of the original bill as amended in the previous session. Public Bills which have not been passed by the end of the session in which they were introduced will otherwise fall. A bill being before the House of Commons, it is necessary for that House to pass a carry over motion in order for the bill to be carried over into the following session. Private Members' Bills cannot be carried over.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/ExplanatoryNote
Object: A document explaining the purpose of a bill. All Government Bills and some Private Members' Bills have explanatory notes. Explanatory memoranda provided alongside a Private Bill are also included in this class.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/PrivateBill
Object: A proposal for a new Act of Parliament differently affecting the interests of particular groups, people or places.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/enactedAs
Object: Relates a bill to the Act of Parliament the bill is enacted as after receiving Royal Assent.
